      <h3 class="Work_heading">Cloud Collectors</h3>
      <p>Elena Maythew, the daughter of a disgraced engineer, is desperate to escape her abusive aunt and make something of herself. Falling off a bridge and being rescued by Anuk, a nitwit with an airship, wasn’t part of her plan.</p>
      <p>If they can stop loathing each other for long enough, they may be able to prevent a war that would destroy both their peoples and become the next generation of Cloud Collectors.</p>
      <hr>
      <p><em>Cloud Collectors</em> is a 75,000-word YA steampunk fantasy set in the skies of the Victorian Era.</p> 
      <p>It is inspired by the Inuit culture of Greenland and the Danish invasions in the 1800s. I’ve spent some time in Greenland, Iceland and Denmark and I couldn’t pick between the three of them for my favourite place to live.</p>
      <p>I’ve had fun with this story, playing around with what it means to be a hero and have power. Neither Anuk or Elena spend a lot of time acting like heroes, even when they think they do. But then adversity reveals character doesn’t it. While there’s airships and some tech the focus for me has always been these two characters that have been in my head for the past seven years. It’s also really important to me that there is a diverse cast in my stories as well. It represents the world we live in.</p>
      <p>Cute story, but if I’d never wrote this book, I wouldn’t have met my fiancé. About five years ago, when I first started writing <em>Cloud Collectors</em>, I had an idea for a charming villain called Aksel, who was tall and thin, with impressive cheekbones.</p>
      <p>One day I was leading a bunch of new exchange students on a university campus tour, when I noticed one particularly attractive man with stunning bone structure, and I thought, ‘he looks just like my character.’ The attractive student introduced himself in his French accent, ‘Erh hello, my name is Axel,’ and I stood there holding his hand for a long awkward amount of time.</p>
      <p>He’s tried to convince me to make Aksel the hero, but sorry my love, no such luck.</p>
